Creating a Virtual Machine (VM) in Azure is one of the most fundamental tasks in cloud computing. It allows users to deploy and run applications on scalable infrastructure without managing physical hardware.

Steps to create a VM:

1. Log in to the Azure Portal
2. Search for “Virtual Machines”
3. Click on “Create” → “Azure Virtual Machine”
4. Select Subscription and Resource Group
5. Enter VM name
6. Choose Region
7. Select Image (e.g., Windows Server, Ubuntu)
8. Choose VM size (CPU, RAM)
9. Configure authentication (username/password or SSH key)
10. Configure networking settings
11. Review and create

For example, a developer can create a Linux VM to host a web application.

A real-life use case is a company hosting its backend services on VMs for full control over the operating system and configurations.

Another example is testing environments where multiple VMs are created for QA testing.

This exercise provides hands-on understanding of deploying compute resources in Azure.
